What a registry actually is.

A container registry is a web service that stores and serves images, speaking a specific h-t-t-p a-p-i called the open container initiative distribution specification. The important point is that every registry, whether docker hub, github's registry, amazon's, or your own private one, implements the very same protocol. The docker client does not know or care which registry it is talking to. It just speaks the standard. Once that clicks, registries stop feeling like magic.

A registry stores two kinds of thing. The first is blobs, which are content-addressable byte storage. Layers are blobs and image configurations are blobs, and each is identified by its s-h-a two-five-six digest, which means uploading the same bytes twice is a no-op, because the second upload sees the digest already exists and skips. The second is manifests, small j-son documents that describe an image as a list of layer digests plus the configuration digest and a little metadata. The manifest itself has a digest, and a tag is simply a mutable pointer from a human name to a manifest digest.

So an image push is really just four steps. Upload each layer's blob, deduplicated by digest so only new layers cross the wire. Upload the configuration blob. Upload the manifest that lists them. And update the tag pointer to the manifest's digest. Pulls are the same steps in reverse. There is no compression magic and no proprietary protocol, just gets and puts against a digest-based content store. Once you hold that, the rest of this notebook is mostly which registry, which credentials, and which tag conventions, because the mechanics never change.
